```ts
function findDuplicates(arr: number[]): number[] {
  const result: number[] = [];
  for (let i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
    for (let j = i + 1; j < arr.length; j++) {
      if (arr[i] === arr[j] && !result.includes(arr[i])) {
        result.push(arr[i]);
      }
    }
  }
  return result;
}
```

📋 SUMMARY: Reviewing your `findDuplicates` function for performance issues.

🔍 ANALYSIS: This is O(n³) — the nested `i`/`j` loops are O(n²), and `result.includes()` inside that adds another O(n) scan on each match. Three layers of linear iteration compound badly as array size grows.

⚡ ACTIONS: Here's an O(n) replacement using a single pass with a `Set`:

```ts
function findDuplicates(arr: number[]): number[] {
  const seen = new Set<number>();
  const duplicates = new Set<number>();
  for (const num of arr) {
    if (seen.has(num)) {
      duplicates.add(num);
    } else {
      seen.add(num);
    }
  }
  return [...duplicates];
}
```

**Why this is faster:**
- `Set.has()` and `Set.add()` are O(1) average, vs O(n) for `Array.includes()`
- Single pass through the array vs nested loop
- Goes from **O(n³)** → **O(n)**

| Array Size | Original (~n³) | Optimized (~n) |
|------------|----------------|----------------|
| 100 | ~1M ops | ~100 ops |
| 10,000 | ~1T ops | ~10K ops |

The output order is preserved as insertion order into the `duplicates` set (first time a duplicate is encountered).

